Project Title: Network Traffic Analyzer for Virtual Environments

Overview
This project demonstrates the implementation and use of a network traffic analyzer to monitor data flow within a virtualized infrastructure. Using Wireshark as the primary analysis tool, I successfully captured and interpreted real-time network packets transmitted between an Ubuntu Linux guest virtual machine and external internet gateways.

The lab highlights the critical relationship between virtualized hardware and the host operating system, specifically focusing on:

Driver Integration: Successfully resolving "unavailable interface" errors by configuring the Npcap packet capture driver on the Windows host.

Live Traffic Monitoring: Capturing ICMP (Ping) requests and replies to verify end-to-end connectivity.

Protocol Analysis: Inspecting Layer 3 (IP) and Layer 4 (ICMP) headers to validate correct packet routing and addressing.

This repository serves as a practical application of networking fundamentals, proving that virtual environments can be effectively audited and monitored for security and troubleshooting purposes.
